🌐 Frontend Configuration
📌 Why Do We Need a Frontend?

Until now, the AI Agent was tested inside the Amazon Bedrock Console.

However, in real-world applications:

Users do not interact via AWS Console
They need a simple UI (chat interface)
They should be able to send messages and receive responses easily

👉 Therefore, we build a web-based chatbot interface that acts as the entry point to the AI system.

🖥️ Frontend Hosting (Amazon S3)

The chatbot UI is built using:

HTML
CSS
JavaScript

👉 Since these are static files, we host them using Amazon S3 Static Website Hosting

✅ Advantages of S3 Hosting
🚫 No server management
💰 Very low cost
⚡ High availability
🚀 Easy deployment
⚠️ Limitation 1 — S3 Frontend Cannot Call Bedrock Directly

A static frontend cannot directly call Bedrock APIs because:

Bedrock requires AWS authentication
Exposing credentials in browser = security risk ❌
🚨 Risks

If we call Bedrock directly from frontend:

Credentials become visible ❌
Anyone can misuse them ❌
🔐 Solution — Chat Proxy Lambda

To solve this, we introduce:

👉 Chat Proxy Lambda

This Lambda acts as a secure backend layer between:

Frontend → Lambda → Bedrock
🎯 Responsibilities of Chat Proxy Lambda
🔐 Securely invoke Bedrock Agent
🛡️ Protect AWS credentials
⚙️ Process agent response
📤 Return response to frontend
⚠️ Limitation 2 — S3 Cannot Call Lambda Directly

👉 Problem:

Browser cannot directly invoke Lambda
Lambda needs a public endpoint
🌍 Solution — API Gateway

We use Amazon API Gateway to expose Lambda via HTTPS.

🔗 Flow
User
 ↓
S3 Chat Interface
 ↓
API Gateway
 ↓
Chat Proxy Lambda
 ↓
Bedrock Agent
 ↓
Action Group
 ↓
Lambda Tool
 ↓
AWS Services

🚀 Final Result
✅ Frontend provides chat UI
✅ API Gateway provides secure endpoint
✅ Lambda protects credentials
✅ Bedrock Agent performs AI reasoning
✅ Full system becomes secure AI automation platform


🔐 — Create IAM Role for Chat Proxy Lambda
📌 Overview

Before creating the Chat Proxy Lambda, we must create an IAM Role.

👉 This role allows Lambda to securely interact with:

Amazon Bedrock
Amazon CloudWatch
🪜 Steps to Create IAM Role
1️⃣ Open IAM
Go to AWS Console → IAM
Click Roles
Click Create role
2️⃣ Select Trusted Entity
Select AWS Service
Choose Lambda
Click Next
3️⃣ Attach Required Permissions

👉 Attach the following:

🔹 1. Custom Bedrock Policy (IMPORTANT)

Since bedrock:InvokeAgent is not a managed policy, create a custom one:

👉 Create Policy → JSON:
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "bedrock:InvokeAgent"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}
👉 Policy Name:
BedrockAgentInvokePolicy
👉 Attach this policy to the role
🔹 2. AWS Managed Policy

Attach:

AWSLambdaBasicExecutionRole

👉 This enables:

CloudWatch logging
Basic Lambda execution
4️⃣ Configure Role
Role Name:
BedrockAgentChatProxyRole
5️⃣ Create Role

Click Create role

✅ Result
Lambda can invoke Bedrock Agent
Logging is enabled
Secure backend communication established

🧠 Key Insight

IAM Roles ensure secure service-to-service communication without exposing credentials.
